#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:5
msgid "Advanced debugging tools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:7
msgid ""
"If you reached here, you want to dive into, or use, more advanced tooling. "
"This is usually not necessary for first time contributors and most day-to-"
"day development. These are used more rarely, for example close to a new "
"NumPy release, or when a large or particular complex change was made."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:13
msgid ""
"Since not all of these tools are used on a regular bases and only available "
"on some systems, please expect differences, issues, or quirks; we will be "
"happy to help if you get stuck and appreciate any improvements or "
"suggestions to these workflows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:20
msgid "Finding C errors with additional tooling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:22
msgid ""
"Most development will not require more than a typical debugging toolchain as "
"shown in :ref:`Debugging <debugging>`. But for example memory leaks can be "
"particularly subtle or difficult to narrow down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:27
msgid ""
"We do not expect any of these tools to be run by most contributors. However, "
"you can ensure that we can track down such issues more easily:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:30
msgid "Tests should cover all code paths, including error paths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:31
msgid ""
"Try to write short and simple tests. If you have a very complicated test "
"consider creating an additional simpler test as well. This can be helpful, "
"because often it is only easy to find which test triggers an issue and not "
"which line of the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:35
msgid ""
"Never use ``np.empty`` if data is read/used. ``valgrind`` will notice this "
"and report an error. When you do not care about values, you can generate "
"random values instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:39
msgid ""
"This will help us catch any oversights before your change is released and "
"means you do not have to worry about making reference counting errors, which "
"can be intimidating."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:45
msgid "Python debug build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:47
msgid ""
"Debug builds of Python are easily available for example via the system "
"package manager on Linux systems, but are also available on other platforms, "
"possibly in a less convenient format. If you cannot easily install a debug "
"build of Python from a system package manager, you can build one yourself "
"using `pyenv <https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv>`_. For example, to install and "
"globally activate a debug build of Python 3.10.8, one would do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:54
msgid ""
"pyenv install -g 3.10.8\n"
"pyenv global 3.10.8"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:57
msgid ""
"Note that ``pyenv install`` builds Python from source, so you must ensure "
"that Python's dependencies are installed before building, see the pyenv "
"documentation for platform-specific installation instructions. You can use "
"``pip`` to install Python dependencies you may need for your debugging "
"session. If there is no debug wheel available on `pypi,` you will need to "
"build the dependencies from source and ensure that your dependencies are "
"also compiled as debug builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:64
msgid ""
"Often debug builds of Python name the Python executable ``pythond`` instead "
"of ``python``. To check if you have a debug build of Python installed, you "
"can run e.g. ``pythond -m sysconfig`` to get the build configuration for the "
"Python executable. A debug build will be built with debug compiler options "
"in ``CFLAGS`` (e.g. ``-g -Og``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:70
msgid ""
"Running the Numpy tests or an interactive terminal is usually as easy as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:72
msgid ""
"python3.8d runtests.py\n"
"# or\n"
"python3.8d runtests.py --ipython"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:76
msgid "and were already mentioned in :ref:`Debugging <debugging>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:78
msgid "A Python debug build will help:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:80
msgid ""
"Find bugs which may otherwise cause random behaviour. One example is when an "
"object is still used after it has been deleted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:83
msgid ""
"Python debug builds allows to check correct reference counting. This works "
"using the additional commands::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:86
msgid ""
"sys.gettotalrefcount()\n"
"sys.getallocatedblocks()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:89
msgid ""
"Python debug builds allow easier debugging with gdb and other C debuggers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:93
#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:187
msgid "Use together with ``pytest``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:95
msgid ""
"Running the test suite only with a debug python build will not find many "
"errors on its own. An additional advantage of a debug build of Python is "
"that it allows detecting memory leaks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:99
msgid ""
"A tool to make this easier is `pytest-leaks`_, which can be installed using "
"``pip``. Unfortunately, ``pytest`` itself may leak memory, but good results "
"can usually (currently) be achieved by removing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:103
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"def add_np(doctest_namespace):\n"
"    doctest_namespace['np'] = numpy\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"def env_setup(monkeypatch):\n"
"    monkeypatch.setenv('PYTHONHASHSEED', '0')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:111
msgid ""
"from ``numpy/conftest.py`` (This may change with new ``pytest-leaks`` "
"versions or ``pytest`` updates)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:114
msgid "This allows to run the test suite, or part of it, conveniently::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:116
msgid ""
"python3.8d runtests.py -t numpy/core/tests/test_multiarray.py -- -R2:3 -s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:118
msgid ""
"where ``-R2:3`` is the ``pytest-leaks`` command (see its documentation), the "
"``-s`` causes output to print and may be necessary (in some versions "
"captured output was detected as a leak)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:122
msgid ""
"Note that some tests are known (or even designed) to leak references, we try "
"to mark them, but expect some false positives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:128
msgid "``valgrind``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:130
msgid ""
"Valgrind is a powerful tool to find certain memory access problems and "
"should be run on complicated C code. Basic use of ``valgrind`` usually "
"requires no more than::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:134
msgid "PYTHONMALLOC=malloc valgrind python runtests.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:136
msgid ""
"where ``PYTHONMALLOC=malloc`` is necessary to avoid false positives from "
"python itself. Depending on the system and valgrind version, you may see "
"more false positives. ``valgrind`` supports \"suppressions\" to ignore some "
"of these, and Python does have a suppression file (and even a compile time "
"option) which may help if you find it necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:143
msgid "Valgrind helps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:145
msgid "Find use of uninitialized variables/memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:147
msgid ""
"Detect memory access violations (reading or writing outside of allocated "
"memory)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:150
msgid ""
"Find *many* memory leaks. Note that for *most* leaks the python debug build "
"approach (and ``pytest-leaks``) is much more sensitive. The reason is that "
"``valgrind`` can only detect if memory is definitely lost. If::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:155
msgid ""
"dtype = np.dtype(np.int64)\n"
"arr.astype(dtype=dtype)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:158
msgid ""
"Has incorrect reference counting for ``dtype``, this is a bug, but valgrind "
"cannot see it because ``np.dtype(np.int64)`` always returns the same object. "
"However, not all dtypes are singletons, so this might leak memory for "
"different input. In rare cases NumPy uses ``malloc`` and not the Python "
"memory allocators which are invisible to the Python debug build. ``malloc`` "
"should normally be avoided, but there are some exceptions (e.g. the "
"``PyArray_Dims`` structure is public API and cannot use the Python "
"allocators.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:168
msgid ""
"Even though using valgrind for memory leak detection is slow and less "
"sensitive it can be a convenient: you can run most programs with valgrind "
"without modification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:172
msgid "Things to be aware of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:174
msgid ""
"Valgrind does not support the numpy ``longdouble``, this means that tests "
"will fail or be flagged errors that are completely fine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:177
msgid "Expect some errors before and after running your NumPy code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:179
msgid ""
"Caches can mean that errors (specifically memory leaks) may not be detected "
"or are only detect at a later, unrelated time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:182
msgid ""
"A big advantage of valgrind is that it has no requirements aside from "
"valgrind itself (although you probably want to use debug builds for better "
"tracebacks)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:188
msgid ""
"You can run the test suite with valgrind which may be sufficient when you "
"are only interested in a few tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:191
msgid ""
"PYTHOMMALLOC=malloc valgrind python runtests.py \\\n"
" -t numpy/core/tests/test_multiarray.py -- --continue-on-collection-errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:194
msgid ""
"Note the ``--continue-on-collection-errors``, which is currently necessary "
"due to missing ``longdouble`` support causing failures (this will usually "
"not be necessary if you do not run the full test suite)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:198
msgid ""
"If you wish to detect memory leaks you will also require ``--show-leak-"
"kinds=definite`` and possibly more valgrind options.  Just as for ``pytest-"
"leaks`` certain tests are known to leak cause errors in valgrind and may or "
"may not be marked as such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:203
msgid "We have developed `pytest-valgrind`_ which:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:205
msgid "Reports errors for each test individually"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:207
msgid ""
"Narrows down memory leaks to individual tests (by default valgrind only "
"checks for memory leaks after a program stops, which is very cumbersome)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_advanced_debugging.rst:211
msgid ""
"Please refer to its ``README`` for more information (it includes an example "
"command for NumPy)."
msgstr ""
